"Arulmozhiraja S., Fujii T.","Li+ ion affinities of global-warming perfluorocarbons",2000,"Journal of Physical Chemistry A","104","42",,"9613","9618",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034293901&partnerID=40&md5=f1dd8d7ac91cdfe5737eb36b87050856","Environmental Chemistry Division, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsiikuba, Ibaraki 305-0053, Japan","Arulmozhiraja, S., Environmental Chemistry Division, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsiikuba, Ibaraki 305-0053, Japan; Fujii, T., Environmental Chemistry Division, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsiikuba, Ibaraki 305-0053, Japan","Density functional theory studies were performed for the first time to obtain the Li+ ion affinities of various perfluorocarbons (PFCs) that cause global-warming. Becke's three-parameter hybrid density functional, B3LYP combined with 6-31G(d), 6-311+G(2d), and 6-311+G(3df) basis sets were utilized for this purpose. We present optimized geometries of PFC-Li+ ion complexes at B3LYP/6-311+G(2d) level. The frequencies obtained at the same level were used to verify all the optimized geometries are minima. The following PFCs-CF4, CHF3, CH2F2, CH3F, C2F6, C4F8, with SF6 - were considered in the present study. The calculated Li+ affinities for CF4, CHF3, CH2F2, CH3F, C2F6, C4F8, and SF6 are 12.31, 19.64, 26.84, 30.10, 17.20, 21.09, and 16.92 kcal/mol, respectively at B3LYP/6-311+G(3df) after zero-point energy and thermal energy corrections. The large Li+ affinities indicate the validity of our proposed Li+ ion attachment mass spectrometry to quantify the emission of these greenhouse gases from semiconductor industries. Complex geometries were obtained and the ion-molecular bonding nature was discussed on the basis of atomic charge, electron density ρ, and its Laplacian. © 2000 American Chemical Society.",,"Global warming; Lithium; Positive ions; Probability density function; Density functional theory (DFT); Perfluorocarbons (PFC); Fluorocarbons",,,,,,"(1900) EPA National Air Pollutant Emissions Trends Report, , The 1998 Report of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency; The 1994 Report of the Scientific Assessment Working Group of IPCC, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC); See the references in refs 12-14Ravishankara, A.R., Soloman, S., Turnipseed, A.A., Warren, R.F., (1993) Science, 259, p. 194; Ramanathan, V., Callis, L., Cess, R., Hansen, J., Isaksen, I., Kuhn, W., Lacis, A., Schlesinger, M., (1987) Rev. Geophys., 25, p. 1441; Stolarski, R.S., Rundel, R.D., (1975) Geophys. Res. Lett., 2, p. 443; Noutary, C.J., (1968) J. Res. Nail. Bur. Stand. Sec. A, 72, p. 479; Winters, H.F., (1987) Su-arm Studies and Inelastic Electron-Molecule Collisions, p. 347. , Pitchford, L. C., McKoy, B. V., Chutjian, A., Trajmar, S., Eds.; Springer: New York; Winters, H.F., Inokuti, M., (1982) Phys. Rev. A, 25, p. 1420; Stepha, K., Deutsch, H., Mark, T.D., (1985) J. Chein. Phys., 83, p. 5712; Brehm, B., Frey, R., Rustier, A., Eland, J.H.D., (1974) Int. J. Mass. Spectrom. Ion Phys., 13, p. 251; Christophorou, L.G., Olthoff, J.K., Rao, M.V.V.S., (1996) J. Phys. Chem. Ref. Data, 25, p. 1341; Christophorou, L.G., Olthoff, J.K., Rao, M.V.V.S., (1997) J. Phys. Chem. Ref. Data, 26, p. 1; Christophorou, L.G., Olthoff, J.K., (1998) J. Phys. Chem. Ref. Data, 27, p. 1; Harnisch, J., Horchers, R., Fabian, P., Maiss, M., (1996) Geophys. Res. Leu., 23, p. 1099; Fujii, T., Ogura, M., Jimba, H., (1989) Anql. Chem., 61, p. 1026; Fujii, T., Syouji, K., (1991) Phys. Rev. A, 46, p. 3555; Fujii, T., (1992) Anal. Chem., 64, p. 775; Fujii, T., (1992) Chem. Phys. Lett., 191, p. 162; Fujii, T., Syouji, K., (1993) J. Appl. Phys., 74, p. 3009; Fujii, T., Syouji, K., (1993) J. Phys. Chem., 97, p. 11380; Fujii, T., Syouji, K., (1994) Phys. Rev. e, 49, p. 657; Fujii, T., Ohta, M., (1995) J. Phys. D. Appl. Phys., 28, p. 1268; Fujii, J.J., (1997) Appl. Phys., 82, p. 2056; Fujii, T., Kim, H.S., (199